items.content: Create a project for each high-level area of your life
Create and nestle any relevant [sub-projects](https://get.todoist.help/hc/en-us/articles/115001862065) underneath each top-level area of your life
Clear your brain – add all the tasks you can think of to the relevant projects
Add [due dates](https://get.todoist.help/hc/en-us/articles/205325931-Due-dates-and-times) to tasks with deadlines you need to remember
Add [recurring due dates](https://get.todoist.help/hc/en-us/articles/360000636289) to tasks that you need to do regularly – like taking out the garbage or submitting a quarterly report
[Connect Todoist to your calendar](https://get.todoist.help/hc/en-us/articles/115003128085-Use-Google-Calendar-with-Todoist) so meetings and appointments show up in your Today & Upcoming views
Make a habit of adding tasks to your Todoist Inbox the moment they come to you
[Download Todoist on your phone](https://todoist.com/downloads/mobile) so you can add tasks on-the-go
[Install Todoist's email plug-ins for Gmail or Outlook](https://todoist.com/downloads/email) to quickly turn emails into tasks
[Install Todoist's browser extensions for Chrome, Safari, or Firefox](https://todoist.com/downloads/browser) to save websites as tasks to come back to later
Pick one important task each day to do first ✅ (just one!)
Get to Todoist Zero 💆‍♀️ (rescheduling isn't cheating!)
Drink 16 oz of water right after you wake up 🚰
Go for a walk outside 🌳 (preferably somewhere green)
Wake up at the same time every day ⏰ (even weekends!)
Do absolutely nothing for 5 minutes 🧘‍♂️ (resist the urge to check your phone!)
Declutter, clean, and organize your space, room by room, at your own pace
Mark tasks as complete as you work through them
Click on the comment icon 💬 below tasks to see more details
If a section isn’t relevant to you, [archive it](https://get.todoist.help/hc/en-us/articles/360007344859-Archive-or-delete-a-section) (e.g. "I don’t have a garage")
**Buy**: Shelf, pantry, and drawer organizers that fit your space
**Buy**: Cleaning supplies like a mop and floor cleaner
**Research**: Look into community charities that take new and used items
**1.** Things will get messier before they get neater
**2.** Be ruthless when it comes to discarding and donating items
**3.** Group like items together as you organize
**4.** Label containers, folders, and boxes for ease
**5.** Find a place for everything and commit to keeping it there
* _Keep your kitchen clean, clutter-free, and functional. Get rid of the food and items you don’t use, so your cooking space doesn’t make you cringe._
Take everything out of your pantry, refrigerator, and freezer
Throw away old and expired food items
Deep clean your empty pantry, refrigerator, and freezer
Put back your food items, organizing them in a way that works for you
Use acrylic storage and labels as needed
Take everything out of your cupboards and cabinets
Do a dinnerware, utensils, glassware, cookware, and tupperware audit
Sort everything into three piles: keep, donate, and toss
Deep clean your cupboards and cabinets
Put back all your cupboard and cabinet items, organizing them in a way that works for you
Do an appliances, accessories, and cookbook audit
Sort everything into three piles: keep, donate, and toss
Put back your appliances, accessories and cookbooks, organizing them in a way that works for you
Tuck away appliances you use infrequently to reduce countertop clutter
Deep clean your microwave, stove, dishwasher

* _Clear out your living room to create the perfect place for weekend movie marathons and curling up with a good book. Get rid of the things that amount to clutter, but keep just enough to keep it cozy. _
Clear out clutter and anything that doesn't quite belong
Sort everything into three piles: keep, donate, and toss
Take a look at old VHS tapes, DVDs, CDs, and records
Assess extra blankets, throws, and pillows
Examine accessories, knick-knacks, and random items
Go through old electronics, stray wires, and random remotes
Put back all your living room items, organizing them in a way that works for you
Swap out old batteries in your remote and electronic devices
Look into innovative ways to manage (and hide) your cords and cables
Switch out any dead or flickering bulbs on lamps and light fixtures
Consider inexpensive baskets, chests, or built-in couch storage for a clutter-free look
* _Keep your room a place for rest and tidy up the things that stress you out. Get rid of old clothes and shoes and craft the right space that’s uniquely you._
Empty out the drawers, night stands, and any shelves
Sort everything into three piles: keep, donate, and toss
Accessories like jewelry, watches, belts, hats, and scarves
Bags, backpacks, wallets, umbrellas, and purses
Underwear, sleep wear, and bathing suits
Put back all your bedroom items, organizing them in a way that works for you
Switch out any dead or flickering bulbs on lamps and light fixtures
Consider inexpensive baskets, chests, or built-in bed storage for a clutter-free look
* _Get rid of lingering junk and sort out a system that keeps your bathroom neat. Make sure everything from toilet paper to sunscreen has a spot._
Sort everything into three piles: keep, donate, and toss
Appliances like curling irons, shavers, straighteners, hair dryers
Skincare like moisturizers, toners, and after-shave
Make-up like lipsticks, foundations, primers, and mascaras
Put back all your bathroom items, organizing them in a way that works for you
Consider inexpensive acrylic dividers and cases for a clutter-free look
* _Stay focused and do your best work in a clean and productive space. Take your office from messy to meticulous with paper and pens in the right place._
Sort everything into three piles: keep, donate, and toss
Office electronics like a webcam, batteries, microphone, headphones
Put back all your home office items, organizing them in a way that works for you
* _Wack away the weeds, clear out the deflated soccer ball, and put away the old toys. Tidy the deck and clean out the shed._
Sort everything into three piles: keep, donate, and toss
Outdoor appliances: hose, sprinkler, snow blower, lawn mower, etc
Games and toys: sports balls, pool noodles, chalk
Put back all your backyard  items, organizing them in a way that works for you
Lawn care and landscaping: mow the lawn, fertilize, water plants, and pull weeds
* _Empty out the old oil canister and toss the dirty rags while keeping all the extras in order. Park your car in a tidy space. _
Empty out the garage including cars, shelves, and cabinets
Sort everything into three piles: keep, donate, and toss
Put back all your garage items, organizing them in a way that works for you
* _Keep your detergent close at hand and the fabric softeners nearby. Tuck everything else away for a later day._
Sort everything into three piles: keep, donate, and toss
Laundry accessories: iron, ironing board, etc
Detergent, dryer sheets, fabric softener, etc
Put back all your laundry room items, organizing them in a way that works for you
Clean out lint from dryer hose
* _Store what you need and bin what you don't. Take out the faded linens you no longer use and keep the decorative pillow shams that spark joy._
Sort everything into three piles: keep, donate, and toss
Bed sheets, pillow cases, shams, and comforters
* _Take away the tripping hazards and keep corridors clear._
Pick up any misplaced and random items
Close all distractions - Do Not Disturb mode
Review past and upcoming calendar items
Create a task to adjust these items
Create a task to plan these items in more detail
Read 6 books before the end of the year
Read one article per day on my industry
Remember to send cards for my friends’ and family’s birthdays
Create a new “Birthdays” project in Todoist

In regards to our conversation last Friday on your desire to expand your skillset so you can better contribute to the agency, I had to think a bit on how this would best work. After a lot of deliberation, the only answer that I could come up with that balances the time we can afford creating training materials/notes vs still being actionable and hitting our goals to grow... would be a more "learn as we go" approach but while taking good notes and frequent check-ins. Ideally, this would be more smooth in the future. But there isn't anything wrong with the learn as we go approach either, that's actually how I learned when I got started.

Some examples of things we'll touch on:
- How would you know if our client's policy (regardless of type) has our agency listed directly as the agency of record or SAN of FL/Comegys?
- Briefly describe the client lifecycle process from when they first contact us or we first contact them, all the way to when they become our client. What happens? What does the sales agent work on for them and if they want to go with us, what happens?
- Basic terms, like premium, issued (policies), carrier, and types of insurance (general descriptions, nothing too deep).

Not sure which areas to include? Do a [Commitment Inventory](https://todoist.com/productivity-methods/commitment-inventory) to identify your high-level priorities

file_attachment.description: The productivity method for people who always have too much on their plate. Make sure that all of your commitments get the time and energy they deserve.
file_attachment.title: The Commitment Inventory: Get More Done By Saying "No"

notes.content: For example, `Grocery List` and `Cleaning` might go under your `Home` project. You might list out each area of work responsibility under your `Work` project. Not all areas of your life need sub-projects.

**Tip:** Color code your projects/sub-projects so you can see at a glance how much attention you're giving each area of your life in your [Productivity view](https://get.todoist.help/hc/en-us/articles/360000410829-How-to-use-the-Productivity-view)

The colors in the graph below represent the colors of the projects of completed tasks. The grey line represents the daily task goal.

Use Todoist's [Google Calendar integration](https://get.todoist.help/hc/en-us/articles/115003128085-Use-Google-Calendar-with-Todoist) so changes you make in your calendar sync back to Todoist and vice versa. You can choose to sync all your Todoist tasks or just specific projects.

We recommend setting up a separate `Meetings & Appointments` project in Todoist to sync with your calendar. That way your events will automatically show up on the right days in your Today and Upcoming views in Todoist, but your calendar won't get cluttered up with all your tasks.

Don't worry about organizing them. We'll get to that later. Just get them out of your head so you can focus on what you're doing in the moment. 

[Learn more about getting the most out of your Inbox](https://get.todoist.help/hc/en-us/articles/360000028960-How-to-best-use-the-Inbox)

This month, make it a habit to pick one (just one!) most important task you want to complete each day. It should be something you can complete in ~1-2 hours. Do you Most Important Task first before everything else gets in the way. 
 
 Even if the rest of your day goes off the rails, you'll still have a guaranteed win. 💪
Learn more about this productivity technique in our [Eat The Frog guide](https://todoist.com/productivity-methods/eat-the-frog).

file_attachment.description: "If it's your job to eat a frog, it's best to do it first thing in the morning." Eat The Frog is the simplest system to make progress on your most important goals.
file_attachment.title: What Is Eat the Frog? A Dead Simple System for Productivity Minimalists

notes.content:
It's a rare day when you finish everything on your to-do list. And that's ok! Todoist Zero doesn't mean completing everything you had planned for the day. It's about rolling with the punches and keeping your to-do list useful and up-to-date. 
 
 This month, take a few minutes at the end of every day to get to "Todoist Zero" – no tasks left for the day. Take stock of your to-do list, complete what you've accomplished and intentionally reschedule everything you didn't get to for later. You can end the work day with the peace of mind that everything's accounted for and you'll start the next day with a realistic plan for getting things done.

"Read 50 books this year" can feel intimidating. "Read for 20 min every day" feels much more doable, and you'll still end up reading books than you otherwise would. 
 
 This month, restart the habit with this daily micro goal. Try doing your 20 minutes of reading [first thing in the morning](https://blog.doist.com/pay-yourself-first/) before life gets in the way.

file_attachment.description: Apply David Bach's personal finance advice to "pay" yourself first by putting your personal “non-negotiables” before work obligations.
file_attachment.title: Want a More Productive Morning Routine? “Pay” Yourself First

notes.content: Bonus tip: Read books you actually enjoy, not just ones you feel you "should" read. If you're looking for recommendations, here are some of the Doist team's [favorite books](https://blog.doist.com/doist-reading-list/) to get started with.

file_attachment.description: Our Doist reading list includes books that inspire us to work differently. From self development to science fiction, these books have shaped our culture.
file_attachment.title: Doist's Reading List: Books For Curiosity, Creativity, and Self-Development

notes.content:
Cleaning up is often the last thing you feel like doing at the end of a long day. Keep clutter at bay by setting a timer and tidying for just 15 minutes a day. At the end of the 15 minutes, give yourself permission to walk away. 
 
 Even if you don't get everything clean, 15 minutes a day will help keep the clutter at bay!

Research [shows](https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4207053/) that even mild hydration can impair cognitive functioning. Mayo Clinic [recommends](https://www.mayoclinic.org/healthy-lifestyle/nutrition-and-healthy-eating/in-depth/water/art-20044256):
 
 - About 15.5 cups (3.7 liters) of fluids a day for men
 - About 11.5 cups (2.7 liters) of fluids a day for women
 
 
 Kick start your hydration for the day by drinking 16 oz of water right after you wake up!

file_attachment.description: Water is a crucial nutrient and euhydration is necessary for optimal daily functioning. Water balance is precisely regulated within the body and many methods exist for assessing hydration status. Cognitive performance measures an individual’s ...
file_attachment.title: The Hydration Equation: Update on Water Balance and Cognitive Performance

notes.content: Walking in nature [has been shown](https://www.nationalgeographic.com/magazine/2016/01/call-to-wild/) to calm the central nervous system, reduce stress, and boost our mood. This month, make a habit of getting outside – preferably somewhere green – for a walk every day. Bonus points if you leave your phone at home!

file_attachment.description: When we get closer to nature—be it untouched wilderness or a backyard tree—we do our overstressed brains a favor.
file_attachment.title: Call to the Wild: This Is Your Brain on Nature

notes.content:
When our wake-up time fluctuates wildly (like when we stay up late and sleep in on weekends), we experience a kind of "[jet lag](https://www.cbc.ca/life/wellness/how-and-why-waking-up-at-the-same-time-everyday-can-improve-your-health-1.4357391)" with our waking hours misaligned with our circadian rhythms. As a result, we wake up groggy and can have a hard time falling asleep when we want to. 
 
 This month, challenge yourself to wake up at the same time every day – even on weekends! – to allow your body clock to reset itself.

file_attachment.description: Stronger immunity, improved concentration and emotional stability could be 40 winks away
file_attachment.title: How and why waking up at the same time every day can improve your health | CBC Life

notes.content:
Mindfulness meditation has been shown to reduce stress, anxiety, and depression and improve focus and memory, among many other benefits. Good news: You don't have to become a monk to enjoy the benefits of mindfulness. 
 
 This month, make a daily habit to give your brain a break from constant stimulation. Set a time and do absolutely nothing for just 5 minutes. Put on some [soothing nature sounds](https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLgdxvG3UlbicrSRyfcSWtCCzxFEO4p7hZ), follow [a guided meditation](https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLgdxvG3Ulbidz8n_l3rZdcAADnDJ6NFHO), or just sit and watch the sunrise in your favorite spot with your morning cup of coffee.

file_attachment.description: Relaxing nature sounds from the Calm app for relaxation, deep sleep and focus.
file_attachment.title: Soothing Sounds

notes.content:
Many of us spend the majority of our days sitting in the same position hunched over computer keyboards. Even if we've ergonomically optimized our workspaces, the human body wasn't built to stay in one configuration for hours at a time. Taking the time to stretch regularly keeps our muscles strong and healthy. 
 
 This month, create a daily habit of setting a timer for 10 minutes and stretching your limbs. You can follow [a guided routine](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4pKly2JojMw) or simply move in a whatever way makes your body feel good.

notes.content:
According to Charles Duhigg, author of [The Power of Habit](https://charlesduhigg.com/the-power-of-habit/), making your bed becomes a keystone habit, something that kick starts a chain of other good decisions throughout the day and gives you a sense of taking charge. You'll start the day off with a small win, feeling more organized and in control. 
 
 Take this month to simply make your bed each morning and see what side effects ripple out into the rest of your day.

Consider cutting back on clutter with storage that helps you keep your food and snacks organized. For instance, put loose granola bags or tea bags in their own dedicated container. Use labels to distinguish loose foods, like "flour" and "sugar".

Look through everything you took out of your cupboards and cabinets, deciding what will be thrown away, donated, and kept. 

Take a look through the following:

* Plates and bowls
* Forks, knives, and spoons
* Serving and cooking utensils
* Glasses, cups, and mugs
* Pots and pans
* Tupperware

Look through everything currently on your countertops, deciding what will be thrown away, donated, and kept.

* Large appliances
* Small appliances
* Cutting boards
* Accessories and knick-knacks
* Cookbooks
